<span id="freeTextContainer15928280802387985118">Both integrity and prudence behoove a reviewer of <i>The Cellar</i>, Richard Laymon’s debut novel, to take it to task for its lazy plotting, its inconsistent characters with their dubious motivations and boring sex scenes, and its exploitation of pedophilia as a means of manipulating the reader to keep turning the page as the author treats these frequent and unpleasant passages of predation as a sort of slapstick. Nonetheless, this particular reviewer must also parrot fellow reviewer Steve’s succinct a</span>
  <span id="freeText15928280802387985118" style="display:none">Both integrity and prudence behoove a reviewer of <i>The Cellar</i>, Richard Laymon’s debut novel, to take it to task for its lazy plotting, its inconsistent characters with their dubious motivations and boring sex scenes, and its exploitation of pedophilia as a means of manipulating the reader to keep turning the page as the author treats these frequent and unpleasant passages of predation as a sort of slapstick. Nonetheless, this particular reviewer must also parrot fellow reviewer Steve’s succinct and revealing <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1465580825?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">assessment</a>—as deplorable a book that the <i>The Cellar</i> remains thirty-eight years after it was first published, it is also ghoulishly entertaining trash that readers of a particular disposition (i.e. freaks) will slurp down like a styrofoam cup of microwaved noodles in a high-cholesterol broth. A creepy house infested with incestuous anthropomorphic rats ever eager for the next bisexual gang bang? Won't find that in the latest bestseller with a dead woman in its title.</span>
